<author><name><![CDATA[lidnariq]]></name></author>
<updated>2013-10-25T17:11:07-07:00</updated>
<published>2013-10-25T17:11:07-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10609&amp;p=119852#p119852</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10609&amp;p=119852#p119852"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Aspect Ratio and Direct3D 9]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10609&amp;p=119852#p119852"><![CDATA[
He's saying:<br />1- Scale up from 256x224 or 256x240 to 512x448 or 512x480, with sample-and-hold interpolation (&quot;nearest neighbor&quot;), such that each single pixel in the input produces four identical adjacent pixels in the output.<br />then<br />2- Scale this 512xY pixmap to 585xY (for NTSC) or 710xY (for PAL) using some fancier interpolation (linear, cubic)<br /><br />This way you get the sharpness of the pixels, without aliasing, and the correct aspect ratio.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3512">lidnariq</a> — Fri Oct 25, 2013 5:11 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
